%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% Managing and Measuring Liquidity %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Managing and Measuring Liquidity}

\subsection{Defining Liquidity Management}
The primary sources of liquidity include: \\
\begin{itemize}
  \item Ready cash balances (cash from bank accounts, payment collections, investment income, liquidation of near-cash securities and other cash flows).
  \item Short-term funds (trade credit, bank lines of credit, short-term investment portfolios).
  \item Cash flow management (the degree of centralization/decentralization of the collections of payments).
\end{itemize}
\hfill \\

Secondary sources of liquidity: \\
\begin{itemize}
  \item Negotiating debt contracts, relieving pressures from high interest payments or principal repayments.
  \item Liquidating assets (hopefully without a substantial loss in value).
  \item Filing for bankruptcy protection and reorganization.
\end{itemize}
\hfill \\

The following major drags on liquidity can occur: \\
\begin{itemize}
  \item Uncollected receivables. 
  \item Obsolete inventory.
  \item Tight credit.
\end{itemize}
\hfill \\

The following major pulls on liquidity can occur: \\
\begin{itemize}
  \item Making payments early. 
  \item Reduced credit limits.
  \item Limits on short-term lines of credit.
  \item Low liquidity positions.
\end{itemize}
\hfill \\

\subsection{Measuring Liquidity}
\[ \text{Current Ratio} = {\text{Current Assets} \over \text{Current Liabilities}} \] 
\hfill \\
\[ \text{Quick Ratio} = {\text{Cash} + \text{Short-Term Marketable Investments} + \text{Receivables} \over \text{Current Liabilities}} \] 
\hfill \\
\[ \text{Accounts Receivable Turnover} = {\text{Credit Sales} \over \text{Average Receivables}} \] 
\hfill \\
\[ \text{Inventory Turnover} = {\text{Cost of Goods Sold} \over \text{Average Inventory}} \] 
\hfill \\
\begin{align*}
\text{Number of Days of Receivables} &= {\text{Accounts Receivable} \over \text{Average Days Sales on Credit}} \\
                                     &= {\text{Accounts Receivable} \over \text{Sales on Credit / 365}} \\
\end{align*}
\hfill \\
\begin{align*}
\text{Number of Days of Inventory} &= {\text{Inventory} \over \text{Average Days Cost of Goods Sold}} \\
                                   &= {\text{Inventory} \over \text{Cost of Goods Sold / 365}} \\
\end{align*}
\hfill \\
\begin{align*}
\text{Number of Days of Payables} &= {\text{Accounts Payable} \over \text{Average Days Purchases}} \\
                                  &= {\text{Accounts Payable} \over \text{Purchases / 365}} \\
\end{align*}
\hfill \\
\[ \text{Operating Cycle} = \text{Num Days of Inventory} + \text{Num Days of Receivables} \]
\hfill \\
\[ \text{Net Operating Cycle} = \text{Operating Cycle} - \text{Num Days of Payables } \]
\hfill \\


