%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% Investing Short-Term Funds %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Investing Short-Term Funds}
\textbf{The discount interest} is the difference between the purchase price and the face value. \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{A nominal rate} is a rate of interest based on the security's face value. (e.g. 5 percent). \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{A yield} is the actual return on the investment if it is held to maturity. \\
\hfill \\
\[ \text{Money Market Yield} = \left({\text{Face Value} - \text{Purchase Price} \over \text{Purchase Price}}\right) \left(360 \over \text{Number of Days to Maturity}\right) \]
\hfill \\
\[ \text{Bond Equivalent Yield} = \left({\text{Face Value} - \text{Purchase Price} \over \text{Purchase Price}}\right) \left(365 \over \text{Number of Days to Maturity}\right) \]
\hfill \\
\[ \text{Discount-Basis Yield} = \left({\text{Face Value} - \text{Purchase Price} \over \text{Face Value}}\right) \left(360 \over \text{Number of Days to Maturity}\right) \]
\hfill \\

A \textbf{passive strategy} is characterized by one or two decision rules for making daily investments. \\
\hfill \\
A \textbf{active strategy} involves constant monitoring and may involve matching, mismatching, and ladder strategies. \\
\hfill \\

A \textbf{matching strategy} is the more conservative of the two and uses many of the same investment types as are used with passive strategies. It involves intentional matching the timing of cash outflows with investment maturities. \\
\hfill \\
A \textbf{mismatching strategy} is the more risky and requires much more accurate cash forecasts. It's possible to use derivatives here. \\
\hfill \\
A \textbf{ladder strategy} is another form of active strategy, which entails scheduling maturities on a systematic basis within the investment portfolio such that investments are spread out equally over the term of the ladder. A laddering strategy falls somewhere between a matching and passive strategy. \\
\hfill \\
Investment returns should be expressed as bond equivalent yields, to allow for comparability among investment alternatives. \\
\hfill \\

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% Managing Accounts Receivable %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Managing Accounts Receivable}
There are three primary activities in accounts receivable management: granting credit and processing transactions, monitoring credit balances, and measuring performance of the credit function. \\
\hfill \\
The goals for the accounts receivable management system include the following: \\
\begin{itemize}
  \item Efficient processing and maintaining accurate, up-to-date records that are available to credit managers and other interested parties as soon as possible after payments have been received. 
  \item Control of accounts receivable and ensuring that accounts receivable records are current and that no unauthorized entry into the accounts receivable file has occurred.
  \item Collection on accounts and coordination with the treasury management function.
  \item Coordination and notification with the credit managers frequently.
  \item Preparation of regular performance measurement reports.
\end{itemize}
\hfill \\

A \textbf{captive finance subsidiary} is a wholly owned subsidiary of the company that is established to provide financing of the sales of the parent company. \\
\hfill \\

The major types of credit accounts include the following: \\
\begin{itemize}
  \item Open book, which is the most common for company to company.
  \item Documentary, with or without lines of credit, most common for cross-border transactions.
  \item Installment credit, with regular timed payments.
  \item Revolving credit.
\end{itemize}

The different forms of terms of credit other than cash include the following: \\
\begin{itemize}
  \item Ordinary terms (e.g. \(net t\) or \(d/t_1 net t_2\) ).
  \item Cash before delivery (CBD)
  \item Cash on delivery (COD)
  \item Bill-to-Bill
  \item Monthly billing
\end{itemize}

A good perfomance measure for check deposits is a calculated \textbf{float factor}. The \textbf{float} in this contet is the amount of money that is in transit between payments made by customers and the funds that are usable by the company. We comput the float factor by dividing the average daily deposit in dollars into the average daily float: \\
\begin{align*}
  \text{Float Factor} &= {\text{Average Daily Float} \over \text{Average Daily Deposit}} \\
                      &= {\text{Average Daily Float} \over \text{Total amount of checks deposited / Number of Days}} \\
\end{align*}
\hfill \\

An \textbf{aging schedule} breaks down the accounts receivable into categories of days outstanding. \\
\hfill \\

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% Managing Inventory %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Managing Inventory}
The \textbf{transactions motive} reflects the need for inventory as part of the routine production-sales cycle. Inventory need is equal to the planned manufacturing activity, and the approach to inventory will be dictated by the manufacturing plan. \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{Precautionary stocks} also may be desirable to avoid any \textbf{stock-out losses}, which are profits lost from not having sufficient inventory on hand to satisfy demand. \\
\hfill \\
A \textbf{economic order quantity-reorder point (EOQ-ROP)} method is based on expected demand and the predictabilty of demand, and it requires determining the level of inventory at which new inventory is ordered. For EOQ-ROP to work well there must be a reliable short-term forecast. \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{Manufacturing resource planning (MRP} systems incorporate production planning into inventory management. \\
\hfill \\

Four components of inventory cost are: \\
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Ordering
  \item Carrying 
  \item Stock-out
  \item Policy (think workers overtime, data processing, training).
\end{enumerate}

