%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% Managing Short-Term Financing %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Managing Short-Term Financing}
\textbf{Committed lines of credit} are the form of bank line of credit that most companies refer to as regular lines of credit. Regular lines are unsecured and are pre-payable without any penalties. \\
\hfill \\

The three major objectives of a short-term borrowing strategy include: \\
\begin{itemize}
  \item Ensuring that htere is sufficient capacity to handle peak cash needs. 
  \item Maintaining sufficient sources of credit to be able to fund ongoing cash needs.
  \item Ensuring that rates obtained are cost-effective and do not substantially exceed market averages.
\end{itemize}
\hfill \\

In addition, there are several factors that borrowers should consider as part of their short-term borrowing strategies: \\
\begin{itemize}
  \item Size and credit-worthiness.
  \item Sufficient access.
  \item Flexibiltiy of borrowing options. 
\end{itemize}
\hfill \\

Calculating the cost of a credit line that requires a commitment fee: \\
\[ \text{Cost} = {\text{Interest} + \text{Commitment Free} \over \text{Loan Amount}} \]
\hfill \\

Calculating the cost of a credit line that is all inclusive: \\
\[ \text{Cost} = {\text{Interest} \over \text{Net Proceeds}} = {\text{Interest} \over \text{Loan Amount} - \text{Interest}} \]
\hfill \\

Calculating the cost of a credit line that has dealer's fees and other fees: \\
\[ \text{Cost} = {\text{Interest} + \text{Dealer's Commission} + \text{Backup Costs} \over \text{Loan Amount} - \text{Interest}} \]
\hfill \\





